cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.MM, cs.NE 

The paper focuses on predicting future frames in natural video sequences, which is a problem in computer vision. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper proposes a novel network architecture for video prediction, which involves learning to discriminate unnatural sequential orders by shuffling the video frames and comparing them to the real video sequence. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper evaluates its proposed method on three datasets with both synthetic and real-world videos, indicating that it may also belong to the sub-category of cs.MM (Multimedia).
